      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\n**Cu²⁺ dominates** with 1,951 distinct ligands — ~43% more than the runner-up Ni²⁺. This reflects copper(II)'s exceptional coordination chemistry: its d⁹ electronic configuration leads to Jahn-Teller distorted square-planar or elongated octahedral geometries that accommodate an enormous variety of donor atoms (N, O, S, P). Cu²⁺ is also biologically ubiquitous and industrially important, driving intense research interest across amino acids, macrocycles, Schiff bases, and countless other ligand families.\n\nThe top 5 are all first-row transition metals (Cu, Ni, Zn, Co, Cd), reflecting the central role of the Irving-Williams series in coordination chemistry research priorities.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
